'''Foodomancy''' was a [[school of magic]] that tapped into ''[[the Art]]'' found in everyday objects. In this school's case, it tapped into magics contained in various exotic food ingredients that, when brought together in a specific manner, resulted in [[enchanted]] wondrous dishes. A person who specialized in foodomancy was called a '''foodomancer'''.{{Cite polyhedron/133/The Gentle Art of Foodomancy|20}}

{{quote|''This is the first of my written tomes which discloses my findings on the school of "Foodomancy." Not a terribly sharp title, I suppose, but it will have to suffice until I think up something wittier.''|[[Jonathan Greenleaf]], a disciple of foodomancy}}

document_data.History:
{{quote|''In any case, I wish you [[Tymora]]'s [[bless]]ing in creating these recipes (even more so in acquiring the actual ingredients!)''|Jonathan Greenleaf}}<br/>
It was believed that the person who re-discovered the foodomancy magic was Jonathan Greenleaf, a magic practitioner and an extraordinary chef of the late 14{{th}} century [[DR]] from the City of Splendors, [[Waterdeep]]. His works were compiled into at least one tome,{{Cite polyhedron/133/The Gentle Art of Foodomancy|21}}

In the late 14{{th}} century DR, Lord [[Raventree]] of Waterdeep got his hands on Jonathan Greenleaf's handwritten [[leather]]-bound works. The noble read the book while sipping on [[Undermountain Alurlyath]]. After completing the work, Lord Raventree set out to find and hire Jonathan Greenleaf as one of his cooks.
